answers.body_markdown:
As a general rule of thumb (from me that is) don&#39;t use `@Cacheable` with JPA entities, this will almost always lead to surprising results/side-effects. 


Imagine the following
```java
public interface SampleRepository extends JpaRepository&lt;Sample, String&gt; {
  
  @Cacheable
  Optional&lt;Sample&gt; findById(String id);

  @Cacheable
  Optional&lt;Sample&gt; findByName(String name);

}
```

Now when retrieving a `Sample` with the `findById` method and changing some properties on it, it will eventually be persisted. Now the `findById` cache has an updated instance of `Sample`. 


Now there is no issue if the `findByName` cache didn&#39;t have the same `Sample` entity as it will be added, however if it did have the same `Sample` entity it would not have the updated record. Even if it references the same data it doesn&#39;t reference the same instance of the `Sample`. 


Which would lead to surprising results. Now ofcourse you could make it so that when you call `save` (which isn&#39;t needed) that it will destroy all caches, but that kind of defeats the purpose of caching. Next to that what if someone doesn&#39;t call save, because it is a managed entity it will automatically persist. 


So instead of using `@Cacheable` here you are better of using the [2nd level cache][1] from the JPA Provider, probably Hibernate. Which will take care of all these things. 

[1]: https://docs.jboss.org/hibernate/orm/6.3/userguide/html_single/Hibernate_User_Guide.html#caching-config

