But note what the Javadocs say about using the `TransactionSynchronizationManager` in your application:

&gt; To be used by resource management code but not by typical application
&gt; code

The solution I finally implemented is to use Spring application events through `ApplicationEvent`, `ApplicationEventPublisher` and `@ApplicationEventListener` with `phase = AFTER_COMMIT`.
Then your async method will be invoked after transaction and entity persistence.

```
public class MyEvent extends ApplicationEvent {
    private Long entityId;
    
    // constructor and getter
    ...
}

@Service
public class SyncService {
    @Autowired
    ApplicationEventPublisher pub;

    @Transactional
    public void mySyncMethod() {
        Entity entity = new MyEntity();
        //fill entity
        dao.save(entity);
        pub.publishEvent(new MyEvent(entity.getId()));
    }
}

@Service
public class AsyncService {
    @Async
    @Transactional
    @TransactionalEventListener(phase = AFTER_COMMIT)
    public void performLongRunningTask(MyEvent event) {
        MyEntity entity = dao.findOne(event.getEntityId());

        // do stuff
    }
}

```

