They (option 1 and 2) are not the same as IODH. The purpose of IODH is to specify that static field will be initialized when `getInstance()` method is called, and not the class is touched by any way. So it makes static reference initialization more explicit. As for reference, this is how IODH looks like:

    public class Singleton {
      private Singleton() {}
    
      private static class Holder {
        private static final Singleton INSTANCE = new Singleton();
      }
    
      public static Singleton getInstance() {
        return Holder.INSTANCE;
      }
    }

In case of eager initialization, whenever a class is referenced in a code at runtime, the class definition (from the .class file) is loaded and all of its static members (incl. static blocks) are initialized. 
For instance, if you have a method like this in your singleton class and you reference it in a client code, (`Singleton.doSomething`), you will see the class gets instantiated despite you are not explicitly calling `getInstance()` method because the static member is getting initialized. 
```
public class Singleton {
  private Singleton() {
      System.out.println(&quot;Singleton initialized&quot;);
  }

  private static Singleton instance = new Singleton();

  private Singleton() {}

  public static Singleton getInstance() {
    return instance;
    }

  public static void doSomething() {
      System.out.println(&quot;Singleton doing something&quot;);
    }
}
```
However, when you do the same thing for IODH singleton, only the `&quot;LazyRegistryIODH doSomething&quot;` message will be printed out to console and the constructor of `LazyRegistryIODH ` is not getting called since there is no static fields or blocks to be initialized.
```
public class LazyRegistryIODH {
    private LazyRegistryIODH() {
        System.out.println(&quot;LazyRegistryIODH initialized&quot;);
    }

    private static class Holder {
        static final LazyRegistryIODH INSTANCE = new LazyRegistryIODH();
    }

    protected static void doSomething() {
        System.out.println(&quot;LazyRegistryIODH doSomething&quot;);
    }

    public static LazyRegistryIODH getInstance() {
        return Holder.INSTANCE;
    }
}
```

