You are trying to effect the stream state from an external source which is generally not a recommended practice. It is not because such operations remove processing guarantees that Kafka Streams library provides.  

The best way of approaching your issue is to use an extra topic. Have your API calls publish the necessary events to that topic, and then use the processor API to properly handle the store from that stream. That way you maintain all the processing guarantees that come with Kafka Streams. It will also allow you to move away from constructing your topology by hand, and rely on the DSL and custom processors. 

Your implementation would look like so:

    @RestController
    public class MyController {
      private final KafkaTemplate&lt;String, MyObject&gt; template;
  
      @PostMapping(&quot;/my-api&quot;)
      public void post(@RequestBody MyObject object) {
        kafkaTemplate.send(&quot;my-topic&quot;, object.getKey(), object);
      } 
    }

Meanwhile your implementation of topology, assuming Processor1 handles your current stream, and ProcessorAPI handles events from API, I also skipped serde details for brevity.

    var stream1 = streamsBuilder.stream(&quot;my-old-topic&quot;)
       .process(() -&gt; new Processor1(&quot;my-store-name&quot;), &quot;my-store-name&quot;);
